\begin_layout Abstract
Bayesian inference provides a principled way of estimating the parameters
 of a stochastic process that is observed discretely in time.
 The overdamped Brownian motion of a particle confined in an optical trap
 is generally modelled by the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process and can be observed
 directly in experiment.
 Here we present Bayesian methods for inferring the parameters of this process,
 the trap stiffness and the particle friction coefficient, that use exact
 likelihoods and sufficient statistics to arrive at simple expressions for
 the maximum aposteriori estimates.
 This obviates the need for Monte Carlo sampling and yields methods that
 are both fast and accurate.
 We apply these to experimental data and compare with commonly used non-Bayesian
 estimation methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the seminal contributions of Rayleigh, Einstein, and Langevin, stochastic
 processes have been used to model physical phenomena in which fluctuations
 play an essential role.
 Examples include the Brownian motion of a particle, the fluctuation of
 current in a resistor, and the radioactive decay of subatomic particles.
 A central problem is to infer the parameters of the process from partially
 observed sample paths, for instance, the diffusion constant from a time
 series of positions, or the resistance from a time series of current measuremen
ts, and so on.
 Bayesian inference provides a principled solution for this inverse problem,
 making optimal use of the information contained in the partially observed
 sample path.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process is commonly used to model the sample paths
 of a harmonically confined Brownian particle.
 This process has a mean regression rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and a volatility 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 which map, in the physical application, to the stiffness 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of the harmonic potential, the friction 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of the particle and the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 of the ambient fluid.
 Since the friction of a particle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=6\pi\eta a$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the viscosity of the fluid, any estimation of the friction also provides
 an estimate of the viscosity of the medium, given the particle radius.
 Thus, the viscosity, which is defined as the macroscopic response of the
 fluid to an externally imposed shear, can be inferred from microscopic
 obversation of the Brownian fluctuations of harmonically confined particle.
 Likewise, the particle diffusion coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 can be inferred from the friction through the Einstein relation 
\begin_inset Formula $D=k_{B}T/\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 These, of course, are consequences of the relation between response and
 correlation that prevails in a physical system in thermal equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we apply Bayesian inference to the problem of estimating
 the parameters of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process from time series that
 represent partially observed sample paths.
 This is of great current experimental relevance, since harmonic confinement
 of micron-sized spheres is easily achieved using optical tweezers.
 A reliable estimation of the trap stiffness is a necessary first step in
 using tweezers for force measurements.
 Bayesian methods, using Monte Carlo sampling, have been proposed earlier
 to this end.
 Here, we present a method that does away with sampling by exploiting the
 exact likelihoods and sufficient statistics of the problem and provides,
 thereby, exact maximum aposteriori parameter estimates in terms of these
 statistics.
 Consequently, the method is both extremely fast and accurate, being able
 to jointly estimate the trap stiffness and the particle friction from a
 time series with a million points in less than a millisecond.
 Further, the fluctuation-dissipation relation provides a stringent internal
 consistency check on the accuracy of the estimation.
 We apply our method to experimental data to find estimates that have excellent
 internal consistency.
 These estimates are found to be in good agreement with commonly used non-Bayesi
an calibration methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remainder of the paper is organized as follows.
 In the next section we recall several key properties of the sample paths
 and distributions of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
 In Section III, we present the Bayesian methods and follow, in section
 IV, with their application to experimental data.
 We conclude with a discussion of future directions in Bayesian inference
 in optical tweezer experiments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Langevin equation for a Brownian particle confined in a potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\dot{v}+\gamma v+\nabla U=\xi
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(t)$
\end_inset

 is a zero-mean Gaussian white noise with variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\xi(t)\xi(t')\rangle=2k_{B}T\gamma\delta(t-t')$
\end_inset

 as required by the fluctuation-dissipation theorem.
 In the limit of vanishing inertia and a harmonic potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\frac{{1}}{2}kx^{2}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the overdamped Langevin equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{x}=-\frac{k}{\gamma}x+\sqrt{\frac{2k_{B}T}{\gamma}}\zeta(t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(t)$
\end_inset

 is now a zero-mean Gaussian white noise with unit variance.
 This is the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process, whose sample paths obey the Ito
 stochastic differential equation, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dx=-\lambda xdt+\sigma dW
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the Wiener process, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=k/\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the mean-regression rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{2k_{B}T\gamma^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 is the volatility.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D=k_{B}T\gamma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=2D.$
\end_inset

 In problems involving Brownian motion, it is convenient to work with the
 diffusion coefficient, rather than the volatility, and therefore we infer
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, directly.
 
\end_layout

