\begin_layout Section
Bayesian inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the time series 
\begin_inset Formula $X\equiv(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{N})$
\end_inset

 consisting of observations of the sample path 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 at the discrete times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=n\Delta$
\end_inset

t with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,\ldots,N.$
\end_inset

 Then, using the Markov property of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process, the
 probability of the sample path is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(X|\lambda,D)=\prod_{n=1}^{N-1}P_{1|1}(x_{n+1}|x_{n},\lambda,D)P_{1}(x_{1}|\lambda,D)
\]

\end_inset

The probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\lambda,D|X)$
\end_inset

 of the parameters, given the sample path, can now be computed using Bayes
 theorem, as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\lambda,D|X)=\frac{P(X|\lambda,D)P(\lambda,D)}{P(X)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $P(X)$
\end_inset

 is an unimportant normalization, independent of the parameters that we
 henceforth ignore.
 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 must be positive, for stability and positivity of entropy production respective
ly, we use informative priors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\lambda,D)=H(\lambda)H(D)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the Heaviside step function.
 This assigns zero probability weight for negative values of the parameters
 and equal probability weight for all positive values.
 The logarithm of the posterior probability, after using the explicit forms
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1|1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

, is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln P(\lambda,D|X) & =\frac{N-1}{2}\ln\frac{\lambda}{2\pi DI_{2}}-\frac{\lambda}{2DI_{2}}\sum\Delta_{n}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & +\frac{1}{2}\ln\frac{\lambda}{2\pi D}-\frac{\lambda}{2D}x_{1}^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we have defined the two quantities 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{2}\equiv1-e^{-2\lambda\Delta t},\quad\Delta_{n}\equiv x_{n+1}-e^{-\lambda\Delta t}x_{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the sum runs from 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,\ldots,N-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum aposteriori (MAP) estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda^{\star},D^{\star})$
\end_inset

 solves the stationary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\ln P(\lambda,D|X)/\partial\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\ln P(\lambda,D|X)/\partial D=0$
\end_inset

, while the standard error of this estimate is obtained from the matrix
 of second derivatives evaluated at the maximum.
 The exact solution of the stationary conditions, derived in the Appendix,
 yields the MAP estimate to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda^{\star} & = & \frac{1}{\Delta t}\ln\frac{\sum x_{n}^{2}}{\sum x_{n+1}x_{n}}\label{eq:map-estimate}\\
D^{\star} & = & \frac{\lambda^{\star}}{N}\left(\frac{\sum\Delta_{n}^{2}}{I_{2}}+x_{1}^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
k^{\star} & = & \frac{\lambda^{\star}}{D^{\star}}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where both 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

 are now evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\lambda^{\star}.$
\end_inset

 The expression for the matrix of second-derivatives is cumbersome and,
 therefore, we evaluate it using automatic differentiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second Bayesian procedure for estimating the trap stiffness alone results
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is interpreted not as a time series but as an exchangeable sequence, or,
 in physical terms, as repeated independent observations of the stationary
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, the posterior probability, assuming an informative prior
 that constrains 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to positive values, is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln P(k|X)=\frac{N}{2}\ln\frac{k}{2\pi k_{B}T}-\frac{1}{2}\frac{k}{k_{B}T}\sum_{n=1}^{N}x_{n}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The MAP estimate straightforwardly follows,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k^{\star}=\frac{Nk_{B}T}{\sum_{n=1}^{N}x_{n}^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This procedure is independent of the sampling time and is equivalent to
 the equipartition method when the Heaviside prior is used for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The posterior probabilities in both methods can be written in terms of the
 four quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}(X)=\sum x_{n+1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}(X)=\sum x_{n+1}x_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}(X)=\sum x_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{4}(X)=x_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which, therefore, are the sufficient statistics of the problem.
 The entire information in the time series 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 relevant to estimation is contained in these four statistics.
 Their use reduces computational expense enormously as only four numbers,
 rather than an entire time series, is required.
 The combination of exact likelihoods, the use of sufficient statistics
 and analytical MAP estimates yields fast and accurate methods for estimating
 parameters from the time series of particle positions.
 This completes our description of the Bayesian procedure for jointly estimating
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, and from there, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A comparison of the estimates obtained from these independent procedures
 provides a check on the validity of the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process as a
 data model.
 Any significant disagreement between the estimates from the two methods
 signals a breakdown of applicability of the model and the assumptions implicit
 in it: overdamped dynamics, harmonicity of the potential, and thermal equilibri
um.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
data acquisition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We collect data on position fluctuations of an optically trapped Brownian
 particle using a standard optical tweezers setup that is described in detail
 in Ref.~
\backslash
cite{rsi12}.
 Here we provide a brief overview.
 The optical tweezers system is constructed around a Zeiss inverted microscope
 (Axiovert.A1) with a 
\begin_inset Formula $100x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $1.4$
\end_inset

 numerical aperture (NA) objective lens tightly focusing laser light from
 a semiconductor laser at 
\begin_inset Formula $1064$
\end_inset

 nm (Lasever, maximum power 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

mW) into the sample.
 The back aperture of the objective is slightly overfilled so as to maximize
 the trapping intensity.
 The sample consists of a dilute suspension (volume fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0.01$
\end_inset

) of polystyrene beads of diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mu$
\end_inset

m in 10% NaCl-water solution, around 
\begin_inset Formula $20\mu l$
\end_inset

 of which is taken on a standard glass cover slip.
 The total power available at the trapping plane is around 15 mW.
 Detection of Brownian motion of a single trapped bead is performed by back-foca
l plane interferometry using the back-scattered intensity of a detection
 laser at 
\begin_inset Formula $671$
\end_inset

 nm that co-propagates with the trapping laser.
 The detection laser power is maintained at much lower levels than that
 required to trap a bead independently.
 The back-scattered signal from a trapped bead is measured using a balanced
 detection scheme that we show in Fig.~
\backslash
ref{fig1}.
 The back- scattered light beam is incident on an edge mirror which divides
 it equally into two halves that are focused using two lenses of equal focal
 length on photodiodes PD1 and PD2 (Thorlabs PDA100A-EC Si-photodiodes having
 bandwidth 2.4 MHz).
 The voltage outputs of PD1 and PD2, i.e.
 A and B, respectively, are then combined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{A-B}{A+B}$
\end_inset

, which gives the normalized value of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinate of Brownian motion at any instant of time.
 The advantage of such balanced detection is that the intensity fluctuations
 of the laser are present in both detection beams simultaneously and are
 thus canceled out when the difference is taken.
 Note that the direction of the edge mirror decides whether the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 coordinate of Brownian motion are being measured with the mirror rotated
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $90$
\end_inset

 degrees to select between the coordinates.
 The photodiodes are much faster than most available commercial quadrant
 photodetectors with a rise time of around 50 ns at highest gain, which
 addresses concerns about photodiode response time and associated requirements
 of data filtering.
 The data from the photodiodes is logged into a computer using a National
 Instruments DAQ system and Labview at a sampling rate of 5 kHz.
 For calibrating the Brownian motion, i.e.
 converting the voltage into physical distance which is necessary for measuring
 the diffusion constant, we employ an acousto-optic modulator that is placed
 in a plane conjugate to the back-focal plane of the microscope objective,
 and scan the trapped bead by known distances and measure the balanced detector
 response according to the method described in Ref.
 ~
\backslash
cite{rsi12}.
 
\end_layout

